    {
      "id": "1a2158d9144b74f3b5cc25dd909bf7c388d65fe6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-11 21:56:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nCommit message needs a rewrite.  The first line short-summary needs to describe what the commit does, not just be the jira ticket's subject.\n\nThe body needs to clearly state what is changed, not just \"pass those configure options\".  The last sentence about kernel modules and mount.lustre location is the main thing, so lead with that.\n\nI question whether we should be supporting something so contrary to the linux Filesystem Hierarchy Standard in the spec file.  The spec file's purpose is specifically to install things in the correct locations for a given platform.\n\nKernel modules go in /lib/modules on RHEL systems (and pretty much any Linux system).  Should we really support Cray's bizarre installation scheme upstream?\n\nHow have they managed to install things using their method in the past?  Why can't they continue to use that method?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "21b80d4e04a631ab8b19e93fc91b615aefa90939",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 6,
        "name": "Cory Spitz",
        "email": "cory.spitz@hpe.com",
        "username": "spitzcor"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-15 04:42:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nIn response to Chris' comments, there is no need to make the spec jump through hoops just to support Cray environments.  If upstream changes that align more closely to the Linux Standard Base File System Hierarchy break Cray, then we'll just have to conform better to the standard.\n\nBut it does make sense for more of the expected autotools behavior to work correctly.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "7da14caf1961c046977ce882ecdbba268044ddf0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-15 16:06:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI think I have to agree with some of the previous comments.\n\nI reviewed this patch a few days ago and felt uneasy about what it was trying to accomplish and decided to sit on it for a bit.\n\nI think ultimately, I feel that this particular patch is trying to achieve multiple goals some which I strongly agree with and others not so much.  I'd like to be able to push forward on the general spec rework (i.e. the removing of hard coding configure arguments in it as a result of the spec.in->spec substing) without the baggage of the rest dragging it down.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "2e67159a4eaa4a52478ed18b167d717910a8e911",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-16 18:15:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nIts not Cray that is interested in the different path options. The sys admins were interested in the ability to have multiple lustre versions stored in the same image. With some script magic the proper tools would be in your path based on the kernel you booted with.I spoke to them about your concerns and they concluded they could live without have modules in a different path than the \"normal\" place. The only one of concern is /sbin/mount.lustre. If you have b1_8, b2_1, and b2_2 in the same image which version of mount.lustre do you get then? Does it work in all cases? Solutions anyone?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "db5142e4b90904d647e5fe274553e713d05f3857",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-16 20:31:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nWhy in the world would you WANT to have different versions installed at the same time in one image when only one can ever be used at a time?  That is just making extra work for oneself (and the packaging system, obviously).\n\nIf you want to have different nodes with different lustres and this is some kind of diskless remote-boot system, I believe that the \"proper\" way to handle that would be to have different images.  That is certainly how we handle our diskless images at Livermore, so I know that can work quite well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "5edf494e4026c83b044c5f9c9a50c98a4b6b4775",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-17 11:36:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nChris is it wrong to have relocatable rpms for lustre? Should configure respect --prefix at all then? I'm not here to argue\nreligion with you but to help meet the requirements of what my team would like to see.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "6fe4c3ad1fd75d5efe930dd964918d335860d671",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 6,
        "name": "Cory Spitz",
        "email": "cory.spitz@hpe.com",
        "username": "spitzcor"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-17 13:28:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nJames, you asked, \"The only one of concern is /sbin/mount.lustre...Solutions anyone?\"\n\nYou can use the Linux alternatives facility and update-alternatives to link /sbin/mount.lustre (and others) to the appropriate version.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "ba4e87fea7bc5c69553114955f9a728a7d0b6016",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-17 14:53:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nCory that is brilliant. Will look into it. I'm also looking at making the rpm relocatable in a cleaner way.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "69659baa49285a3a95283f6cfe41294d34d74a85",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-17 17:02:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nThe kernel modules just aren't relocatable.  Each distro has a very specific way that they should be installed.  So I don't think we should even attempt it with the \"lustre-modules\" rpm.\n\nNow the \"lustre\" rpm could perhaps be reasonably made relocatable...but since the binaries are largely tied to the version of the modules (at least between major lustre releases), and the modules are not relocatable, what does that buy us?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "d5251cef90f19f5af438b5891ec238cec7ee4dd2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-17 17:35:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nYes modules are not relocatable. Chris I believe this should be brought to the community to decided if they want this feature. I believe its up to the community to make this choice.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
